SM121 (DGX Spark GB10) shared memory fix for cutlass_moe_fp4 / nvfp4_blockwise_moe

Problem:
  Both SM120 (RTX 5090, RTX PRO 6000 Blackwell) and SM121 (DGX Spark GB10)
  provide only 99 KiB (101376 bytes) of shared memory per thread block.
  The 228 KiB figure that's often cited for "Blackwell" belongs to SM100
  (B200), not SM12x — per CUTLASS maintainer @depaulmillz in
  NVIDIA/cutlass#3144.

  CUTLASS's run_fp4_blockwise_scaled_group_mm_sm120() path in
  nvfp4_blockwise_moe.cuh uses the Pingpong ptr-array schedule with
  ThreadBlockShape<_128, _128, _128>. Together with StageCountAutoCarveout
  this requests mainloop SMEM that exceeds the 99 KiB device budget.
  The CUDA runtime then triggers a device-side assert inside the kernel
  launch path, which surfaces in userspace as a "device-side assert
  triggered" at nvfp4_blockwise_moe.cuh:78 (the next cudaMallocAsync
  sync-point on the stream, NOT the root cause line).

  Confirmed trigger on DGX Spark: any NVFP4 model (Qwen3-235B-A22B-NVFP4,
  GLM-4.7-NVFP4, Qwen3.5-397B-A17B-NVFP4, etc.) run with
  moe_runner_backend=triton or =cutlass under SGLang v0.5.10. The
  flashinfer_cutlass backend avoids this path entirely and works fine.

Fix:
  Two independent edits, both required.

  1. ThreadBlockShape N halved from 128 to 64.
     Shape<_128, _128, _128> → Shape<_128, _64, _128>.
     The mainloop SMEM for the B-operand is proportional to N, so halving
     N roughly halves the B footprint. This is the *load-bearing* change
     that makes the total SMEM fit within 99 KiB. Cost: more tiles per
     problem → slightly more kernel launches (single-digit % overhead
     expected on typical Qwen3 MoE shapes).

  2. Ptr-array schedule Pingpong → Cooperative.
     KernelPtrArrayTmaWarpSpecializedPingpong →
     KernelPtrArrayTmaWarpSpecializedCooperative.

     Cooperative runs both math warp groups on the SAME output tile
     (split along M); they share mainloop buffers. Pingpong runs the
     groups on DIFFERENT tiles concurrently, which requires more
     peak SMEM for the concurrent buffering.

     The Sm120 block-scaled CollectiveBuilder at
     cutlass/gemm/collective/builders/sm120_blockscaled_mma_builder.inl:72
     explicitly accepts BOTH Pingpong and Cooperative as valid tags for
     ArchTag=Sm120 + OpClassBlockScaledTensorOp, so Cooperative is a
     drop-in replacement — no other template parameter needs to change.

     Earlier iterations of this patch tried Cooperative alone (without
     the tile-N halving) and still failed at runtime. The schedule swap
     is NECESSARY but NOT SUFFICIENT on GB10's 99 KiB budget; the tile
     shrink in hunk 1 is what decisively brings the footprint under the
     budget.

  StageCountAutoCarveout is kept unchanged. With the smaller tile +
  Cooperative's lower buffering, the automatic stage count calculation
  picks a valid pipelining depth from the remaining SMEM budget without
  any manual override.

  An earlier broken variant used StageCount<1> or StageCount<2> with
  a schedule tag `KernelPtrArrayTmaWarpSpecialized` that does not
  exist in CUTLASS — only the Pingpong and Cooperative suffixed
  variants are defined. That variant failed CUTLASS SFINAE with 17
  cascading "incomplete type" errors on every GemmKernel reference
  downstream. The correct fix is the schedule swap + tile shrink.

  This follows the same general approach TensorRT-LLM merged in PR #12141
  (2026-03-18) for the analogous fp4_gemm_template.h path on SM121, though
  their fix operates on a different layer of the CUTLASS stack.

Refs:
  - https://github.com/NVIDIA/cutlass/issues/3144
      Root cause. Contains the verbatim SMEM numbers above
      (228 KiB SM100 vs 99 KiB SM120/121).
  - https://github.com/NVIDIA/TensorRT-LLM/pull/12141
      Reference fix from NVIDIA maintainers for the TRT-LLM FP4 GEMM path.
  - https://github.com/sgl-project/sglang/pull/20012
      JIT migration: the target file moved from sgl-kernel/csrc/moe/
      to python/sglang/jit_kernel/csrc/moe/.

Upstream source: sgl-project/sglang tag v0.5.10

--- a/python/sglang/jit_kernel/csrc/moe/nvfp4_blockwise_moe.cuh
+++ b/python/sglang/jit_kernel/csrc/moe/nvfp4_blockwise_moe.cuh
@@ -290,7 +290,13 @@
   using ArchTag = cutlass::arch::Sm120;
   using OperatorClass = cutlass::arch::OpClassBlockScaledTensorOp;
   using StageCountType = cutlass::gemm::collective::StageCountAuto;
-  using ThreadBlockShape = Shape<_128, _128, _128>;
+  // dgxarley sgl-kernel-sm121.patch: ThreadBlockShape N halved from 128 to 64.
+  // The Cooperative schedule swap alone (hunk 2 below) was not enough to bring
+  // the mainloop SMEM footprint under SM121's 99 KiB budget — the CollectiveBuilder
+  // still exceeded it. Halving the N dimension cuts the B-operand SMEM in half
+  // which is comfortably below the budget. Tradeoff: more tiles per problem and
+  // slightly more kernel launches. See patch header and CUTLASS#3144.
+  using ThreadBlockShape = Shape<_128, _64, _128>;
   // on the tile size

   using ClusterShape = Shape<_1, _1, _1>;
@@ -329,7 +335,13 @@
       ClusterShape,
       cutlass::gemm::collective::StageCountAutoCarveout<static_cast<int>(
           sizeof(typename CollectiveEpilogue::SharedStorage))>,
-      cutlass::gemm::KernelPtrArrayTmaWarpSpecializedPingpong>::CollectiveOp;
+      // SM120/121 have 99 KiB SMEM/block — not 228 KiB like SM100 (see
+      // CUTLASS#3144). Pingpong duplicates mainloop buffers across its
+      // two persistent math warp groups. Cooperative lets both groups
+      // share buffers on the same tile. This alone is insufficient on
+      // GB10 — see the ThreadBlockShape hunk above which halves the
+      // tile N dimension to bring total SMEM decisively under budget.
+      cutlass::gemm::KernelPtrArrayTmaWarpSpecializedCooperative>::CollectiveOp;

   using GemmKernel = cutlass::gemm::kernel::GemmUniversal<ProblemShape, CollectiveMainloop, CollectiveEpilogue>;
